Students are already overloaded with platforms, courses, and coding clubs. If this feels like “just another tool,” adoption will stall after curiosity.

To win Indian colleges, this has to feel like:

> **a movement + a career advantage + a social identity**

---

# 🚀 Go-To-Market Strategy: Indian Colleges

Product: GitHub Learn (on GitHub)

---

# 1. 🎯 Market Segmentation

## Tier 1: Elite Colleges (High leverage)

* IITs, IIITs, BITS, top NITs
* Students already on GitHub
* Competitive, status-driven

👉 Goal: **Create Credibility + Early Evangelists**

---

## Tier 2: Private Engineering Colleges (Volume play)

* VIT, SRM, Manipal, Amity, etc.
* High aspiration, lower direction

👉 Goal: **Drive adoption at scale**

---

## Tier 3: Mass Colleges (Long tail)

* State colleges, Tier 3 cities

👉 Goal: **Later expansion via community + referrals**

---

# 2. 🧠 Positioning (Critical)

Avoid:

> “Learn coding on GitHub” ❌

Position as:

> **“Build real projects that get you hired”**

Core hook:

* Not learning
* Not coding
  👉 **Getting industry-ready**

---

# 3. ⚡ Core GTM Engine

## 🔁 Flywheel:

**Campus Influencers → Community → Social Proof → FOMO → Adoption → Showcase → Hiring Outcomes → More Adoption**

---

# 4. 🧩 GTM Channels

---

## 4.1 🎓 Campus Ambassador Program (Primary Driver)

### Build: “GitHub Builders Program”

### Who:

* Top 1–2 students per college
* Already active on GitHub / coding clubs

### What they do:

* Run project-building cohorts
* Host hack sessions
* Share progress publicly

### Incentives:

* GitHub certifications
* Direct visibility to recruiters
* Swag + recognition
* Access to GitHub/Microsoft engineers

---

## 4.2 🏆 Flagship Campaign: “Build in Public India”

### Concept:

Students document their journey:

> “0 → 1 project in 30 days”

### Platforms:

* LinkedIn
* Instagram

### Mechanics:

* Daily/weekly updates
* Use hashtag: #BuiltOnGitHub

### Outcome:

* Social proof
* Peer pressure (FOMO)
* Visibility for students

---

## 4.3 ⚔️ Inter-College Build Battles

### Format:

* College vs College competitions
* Real-world problem statements

### Example:

> “Build a fintech product in 7 days”

### Why it works:

* Indians are highly competitive
* Adds urgency + excitement

---

## 4.4 🧪 Guided Cohorts (High Conversion Layer)

### Format:

* 2–4 week structured programs

### Example:

* “Build Your First SaaS”
* “Backend Engineering Bootcamp”

### Run by:

* Campus ambassadors + GitHub

### Outcome:

* Deep engagement
* High completion rates

---

## 4.5 🤝 College Partnerships

### Target:

* Training & Placement Cells
* Coding clubs

### Pitch:

> “Improve placement outcomes with real project portfolios”

### Integration:

* Replace mini-projects with GitHub Learn projects

---

## 4.6 🎥 Content Engine (Underrated but Powerful)

### Content Types:

* “What I built in 7 days”
* “From zero to deployed app”
* “Why recruiters rejected my resume before this”

### Platforms:

* YouTube
* Instagram

### Strategy:

* Partner with dev influencers
* Push relatable journeys (not polished tutorials)

---

## 4.7 🏢 Hiring Integration (Ultimate Hook)

### Feature:

* “Get Discovered” badge on GitHub

### Partner with:

* Startups hiring freshers

### Outcome:

* Real interviews based on projects

👉 This is your **strongest conversion lever**

---

# 5. 🧲 Activation Strategy (First 30 Days)

---

## Week 1–2: Awareness

* Ambassador announcements
* Influencer content drops
* College WhatsApp/Discord penetration

---

## Week 2–4: Engagement

* Start Build Cohorts
* Launch Build in Public challenge
* First inter-college battle

---

## Week 4+: Retention

* Showcase top projects
* Highlight success stories
* Push second project journeys

---

# 6. 📊 Metrics (GTM Specific)

---

## Top of Funnel

* # colleges onboarded
* # ambassadors activated
* Reach (views, impressions)

---

## Activation

* % users starting first project
* Cohort participation rate

---

## Engagement

* Weekly Active Builders
* Posts per user (build in public)
* Tasks completed

---

## Retention

* % users starting second project
* Cohort completion rate

---

## Social Proof

* # public project shares
* # hashtag usage (#BuiltOnGitHub)

---

## Hiring Impact (Critical)

* # recruiter views
* # interview invites
* # hires

---

# 7. 🎯 Success Milestones

---

## Month 3:

* 100+ colleges onboarded
* 25K+ active student builders
* Strong social presence

---

## Month 6:

* 100K+ users
* 40%+ project completion rate
* Recognizable campus brand

---

## Month 12:

* Default platform for project building
* Recruiters actively sourcing
* GitHub profiles = hiring signal

---

# 8. ⚠️ Risks & Mitigation

---

## ❌ Low Participation

👉 Fix:

* Strong ambassador selection
* Incentive-driven cohorts

---

## ❌ Drop-offs mid-project

👉 Fix:

* Break projects into milestones
* Public accountability (build in public)

---

## ❌ Becomes “just another course”

👉 Fix:

* Focus on shipping + showcasing
* Avoid passive content

---

## ❌ Weak community

👉 Fix:

* Highlight top builders
* Reward contributors, not lurkers

---

# 9. 🔥 Strategic Insight (This is the unlock)

Indian students don’t adopt tools for:

* Learning ❌

They adopt tools for:

* Placements
* Status
* Peer validation

👉 Your GTM must optimize for:
**Career outcomes + social visibility + competition**

---

# 10. 🏁 Final Take

If executed well, this becomes:

> “If you’re serious about getting a tech job, you *have* to build on GitHub.”

That’s when:

* Adoption becomes organic
* Community becomes self-sustaining
* And GitHub becomes the **default career platform for developers in India**

